[Type 2 diabetes in the elderly, which specific features?].

[Article in French]

Graillot D(1), Quipourt V, Bouillet B, Petit JM, Manckoundia P.

Author information:
(1)Service de Médecine Interne Gériatrie, Hôpital de Jour, Centre de 
Champmaillot, CHU de Dijon, 2, rue Jules-Violle, BP 87 909, 21079 Dijon cedex, 
France.

Type 2 diabetes, whose prevalence has increased among elderly aged over 
75 years, has a number of specific features which differ from that in young 
people: heterogeneous population, association with other cardiovascular risk 
factors and several comorbidities, different therapeutic constraints and risks, 
and lower life expectancy. By using a standardized geriatric assessment it is 
possible to determine therapeutic and glycemic goals for each patient. In the 
elderly, main complications of diabetes are hypoglycemia and foot lesions. In 
order to avoid malnutrition, lifestyle and dietary rules should not be too 
strict. Recommendations for the prescription of oral antidiabetic agents are the 
same for both elderly and young subjects, but with increased monitoring in the 
elderly because of the high risk of complications including iatrogenic 
hypoglycemia. Insulin therapy should be preferred.

